        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We opt to observe CO(3-2) rather than CO(2-1) for two important reasons: 1) The continuum is a factor of &gt;5 brighter at CO(3-2), allowing us to simultaneously constrain the cold gas and dust morphology, and 2) We have already measured the integrated CO(3-2) flux with the Submillimeter Array, allowing us to estimate the required ALMA exposure time without the use of a highly-uncertain (factor of 2-3) CO (2-1)/(3-2) correction. While it would undoubtedly be useful to have CO(2-1) to help constrain both the total gas content and the excitation temperature, the immediate goals of this program (CO+dust morphology, CO kinematics) are best achieved with the CO(3-2) transition.

We begin with the peak CO(3-2) line flux from our Submillimeter Array observations (McDonald+13c) of 12 mJy/beam. We opt for an angular resolution of 0.7" (~10x finer than our SMA observations), which matches both our Chandra ACIS-I (0.8") and Gemini-GMOS (0.7") observations, allowing us to compare the hot, warm, and cold gas on similar spatial scales (~5 kpc) (see Figure 1). The extent of the H_beta emission is such that it is fully covered by 8 beams with FWHM=0.7, so we require sensitivity to sources with flux greater than 12/8 = 1.5 mJy. We opt for 25 km/s binning, allowing us to resolve velocity structure  on the order ~10 km/s - similar to that observed in Abell 1835 with ALMA (McNamara et al. 2013).

To reach peak S/N=5 (N=0.3 mJy) with 25 km/s bins, we require a total exposure of 2.41h, with 1.20h on source. We note that if the extended emission is significantly fainter, we can bin to ~200 kms in order to boost the S/N (see Figure 2) by a factor of ~3 at the expense of fine velocity resolution and at the risk of potentially blending multiple velocity components. This exposure also yields S/N=8.5 on the continuum, allowing us to simultaneously measure both the CO and far-IR morphology.

These observations are improved over our published SMA CO(3-2) program (McDonald+13c) by a factor of ~10 in angular resolution (FWHM: 7.5"-&gt;0.7") and ~40 in sensitivity (noise: ~4mJy-&gt;0.1mJy per beam in 200km/s wide bins; Figure 2), allowing for roughly a factor of 400 improvement in depth at a cost of only 2.4h (compared to ~8h with SMA). This dramatic improvement in data quality will allow us to map out both the CO(3-2) and dust morphology, as well as study the spatially-resolved CO kinematics.</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
